Conversely, how can I convert a PowerPoint outline into Markdown?
Absolutely â€” converting a PowerPoint outline back into Markdown is possible, and it can be very useful if you want to edit content as text, version-control your slides, or generate documentation from your presentation. Hereâ€™s how to do it systematically:
ğŸ§© Goal
Convert a PowerPoint outline into Markdown where:
Slide titles become # H1 headings
Bullet points become - or sub-bullets ( -)
Sub-bullets become deeper indents ( -)
ğŸ§­ Step-by-Step Methods
Method 1: Export as Outline / Text and Convert Manually
Open the PowerPoint presentation.
Go to File â†’ Export â†’ Create Handouts â†’ Create Outline in Microsoft Word.
This creates a Word document with slide titles and bullet points.
Open the Word document and save it as .txt.
Convert text to Markdown manually:
Slide titles â†’ # Slide Title
Top-level bullets â†’ - Bullet
Sub-bullets â†’ - Sub-bullet
Example:
The Importance of the PowerPoint Outline Function
The Outline Encourages Conceptual Thinking Before Design
Focuses on main arguments, logical sequence, and supporting evidence
The Outline Clarifies Structure and Hierarchy
Method 2: Copy Outline View Directly
In PowerPoint, go to View â†’ Outline View.
Select all text in the Outline pane (Ctrl+A â†’ Ctrl+C).
Paste it into a text editor.
Add Markdown formatting:
Lines ending with : or bold text â†’ # Slide Title
Indented text â†’ - Bullet or - Sub-bullet
Method 3: Use Python for Automated Conversion
If you want to automate conversion from .pptx to Markdown:
```python
from pptx import Presentation
prs = Presentation("presentation.pptx")
with open("presentation.md", "w") as md_file:
    for slide in prs.slides:
        # Slide title
        if slide.shapes.title:
            md_file.write(f"# {slide.shapes.title.text}\n")
        
        # Slide content
        for shape in slide.shapes:
            if shape.has_text_frame and shape != slide.shapes.title:
                for para in shape.text_frame.paragraphs:
                    indent = "  " * (para.level if hasattr(para, 'level') else 0)
                    md_file.write(f"{indent}- {para.text}\n")
```
âœ… This will generate a Markdown file where:
Each slide title â†’ # Slide Title
Bullets/sub-bullets â†’ properly indented - lists
Requirements:
pip install python-pptx
Tips
PowerPoint Element Markdown Equivalent
Slide title # Slide Title
Top-level bullet - Bullet
Sub-bullet - Sub-bullet
Notes section Can be included as > Notes: â€¦ if needed
